<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-285-322  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 285 322.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  May 1989 v12 n5 p85(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Large-format scanners. (architecture, engineering, andconstruction computer-aided design, includes related articleentitled 'aperture card scanners') (buyers guide)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lang, Laura.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Scanner technology has rapidly changed due to high-tech wizardryand the market is one of the fastest growing in the graphicsindustry.andP;  Large-format scanners are selling quickly both asstand-alone systems and bundled with other graphics equipment.andO;About 400 scanners worth about $85,000 each were sold in 1987 and800 are expected to be sold in 1989.andP;  Analysts expect that 1,300 ayear will be shipped by 1992.andP;  Large-format scanners can becategorized into three areas: engineering document automation,computer-aided design conversion, and mapping.andP;  These three areasare served by three main types of scanners: drum, laser, andcharged coupled device (CCD) technologies.andP;  The largest change inthe scanner market is the fact that scanners are now seen as a newlink between other system entities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Aided DesignScanningImaging TechnologyMarket PenetrationMarket Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   A scan of large-format vendors. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>